Predicting the Valence of Pop Songs through Spotify's Audio Features
¶

CMSC320 Data Science Final Tutorial
¶

Tutorial by Dylan Nguyen

Image from Spotify

Motivation
¶

Music is great! And Spotify is one of the most popular music streaming platforms in the United States. I can attest to that by saying I am one of its daily users.

While I was brainstorming ideas for a potential final project, music was at the top of my list of interests. I looked especially for any dataset related to Spotify. One of my favorite music genres is pop music! When I listen to pop music, I am generally trying to get into a good mood or am in a good mood. As I explored what types of data was available, I found a dataset with an audio feature called Valence which caught my attention. Valence is the measure of musical postiveness conveyed by a song. Or in other words, the measure of happiness in a song! Pop music plays a large role in my life in cheering me up or enjoying time with friends, so exploring a pop song's valence is compelling to me. This is why I wanted to research more into it and hopefully figure out if there is some relationship or outcome I can find with the Valence of a song.

Gathering Data
¶

I explored different datasets available on Kaggle. I really liked how Kaggle provides free, easy to use, and organized data so gathering data is easier! There were a lot of Spotify related datasets, but I settled with the one with the most data (about 2000 songs available) and interesting attributes to look at. This dataset represents the top 2000 songs on spotify. This dataset contains audio statistics of the top 2000 tracks on Spotify. Each column had a unique audio feature rating for songs. Some interesting column names that I found interesting were Valence, Danceability, and Energy. There is also a Popularity column that will also be put into the same grouping as Audio Feature. It is not necessary an attribute that contributes the song's audio, but will be interesting to look at. It is important to note there are a lot of genres in this dataset, so creating a subset for pop songs will be necessary and explained in a later section.

The dataframe contained the following content:

  • Index: ID
  • Title: Name of the Track
  • Artist: Name of the Artist
  • Top Genre: Genre of the track
  • Year: Release Year of the track
  • Beats per Minute(BPM): The tempo of the song
  • Energy: The energy of a song - the higher the value, the more energtic. song
  • Danceability: The higher the value, the easier it is to dance to this song.
  • Loudness: The higher the value, the louder the song.
  • Valence: The higher the value, the more positive mood for the song.
  • Length: The duration of the song.
  • Acoustic: The higher the value, the more acoustic the song is.
  • Speechiness: The higher the value, the more spoken words the song contains
  • Popularity: The higher the value, the more popular the song is.

Let's now create a heatmap to see if there is any correlation between the audio features!

sns.heatmap(heats, 
            cmap = sns.diverging_palette(250, 30, l=65, center="light", as_cmap=True),
            square=True,
            center = 0,
            annot=True)

plt.show()

In order to read this heatmap, it is important to understand that:

  • Every square shows the correlation between the audio features.
  • The correlation ranges will be from -1 to 1.
  • Values closer to 0 means there is no linear relationship between the two audio features. In our heatmap, it'll appear more white colored.
  • Values closer to 1 means the correlation is more positively correlated. This will appear more orange.
  • Values closer to -1 means that one audio features's values decreases while the other audio features increases. This will appear more blue.
  • It is okay to ignore the diagonal values with 1 since it is just audio features correlating to itself.

From eyeballing at this heatmap, we can see that there are some interesting correlation occuring between audio features.

  • Energy and Loudness have the highest correlation of 0.73 compared to their neighboring audio features. We can also tell from its vivid orange color.
  • Acousticness and Energy have the lowest value among the -1 to 1 range with -0.7 which is apparent from its bluer color.
  • Liveness and Loudness have the value of 0.1. This is the closest value to 0 meaning little to no correlation. This is displayed as white.

Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning
¶

The goal is to use machine learning to predict the Valence in pop songs. There are 9 other audio features to look into and inspect their impact on a song's Valence. Linear Regression will be used to model the relationship between two variables by fitting a linear equation to observed data. A linear regression line has an equation of the form Y = a + bX. X is the explanatory variable while Y is the dependent variable.

Null Hypothesis:¶

  • There are some relationship between Valence of a song and other audio features!

Statsmodel's Ordinary Least Square Model (OLS)¶

We will use this model to create a linear regression model. The dependent variable is Valence while the independent variables will be the other audio features (Beats Per Minute (BPM), Energy, Danceability, Loudness (dB), Liveness, Length (Duration), Acousticness, Speechiness, Popularity).

Linear Regression¶

We will attempt to measure how close data points are to the fitted regression line by calculating the R-squared score.

  • The scores range from 0 to 1
  • The closer the value to 1, the more accurate the data is. The closer the value is to 0, the more inaccurate data is.



Most of the concepts used here will not need to be done from scratch since there are libraries and existing implementations we imported earlier in the tutorial. We will mainly use sklearn, which is a popular machine learning libary with a variety of features that will aid us in exploring our hypothesis. More information on the Least Ordinary Square and Linear Regression provided at the end of the tutorial.

In [226]:
# audio_feats will exclude Valence
audio_feats = ['Beats Per Minute (BPM)','Energy', 'Danceability', 'Loudness (dB)', 
               'Liveness', 'Length (Duration)', 'Acousticness', 'Speechiness', 'Popularity']


x = pop_songs[audio_feats]  # Dataframe that holds all the audio features apart from Valence
y = pop_songs['Valence']  # Dataframe that holds all the Valence related stats

# Fits the data and helps us look at a Least Ordinary Square summary 
ols = api.OLS(y,x).fit()
ols.summary2()

We can see that there is quite a bit of information to take in from this table. While there are other interesting areas to look at, the most important column we should look at currently is the P>|t| column. This is the p-value of each audio feature!

  • P-Value: Probability that the null hypothesis is true.
  • P-Value Range: -1 < c < 1, with 1 being linear positive and -1 being linear negative slope.
  • If a P-Value is less than 0.05, this means there is a higher statistical significance.

We can see that Loudness (dB) and Popularity have a lower value than 0.05! This is important because it tells us that our null hypothesis is true and that there is significant correlation! We can also see that there are some values in the column that are just 0.0 values. This is strange and could be a result of the summary not showing more decimal numbers.

Luckily, there is a way to output the p-values directly. Check out the code below:

We can also use Pearson's correlation to see another perspective on our p-values from earlier. Pearson's correlation coefficient is used to summarize the strength of the linear relationship between two data samples. We will check the p-values of Energy, Danceability, Loudness, and Popularity to Valence.

In [228]:
# Getting the P-Values through Pearson's correlation coefficient method
print("Pearson's Correlation P-Values:")
p = pearsonr(data['Valence'], data['Energy'])
print("P-Value for Valence and Energy:", p[1])
p = pearsonr(data['Valence'], data['Danceability'])
print("P-Value for Valence and Danceability:", p[1])
p = pearsonr(data['Valence'], data['Loudness (dB)'])
print("P-Value for Valence and Loudness (dB):", p[1])
p = pearsonr(data['Valence'], data['Popularity'])
print("P-Value for Valence and Popularity:", p[1])
print('\n')

Pearson's Correlation P-Values:
P-Value for Valence and Energy: 1.1877862303821174e-79
P-Value for Valence and Danceability: 3.1208607711013127e-135
P-Value for Valence and Loudness (dB): 4.1735452163699535e-11
P-Value for Valence and Popularity: 1.786482609798892e-05

We can see that the P-values calculated through Pearson's correlation coefficient shows similar outcomes and trend as the OLS summary's values.

We will agree with the null hypothesis!

Prediction of Valence Based on Other Features¶

Here we will use sklearn and their linear_model capabilities.

In [229]:
lr = linear_model.LinearRegression().fit(x,y)
rsquared = lr.score(x,y)
print("R-squared Value:",rsquared)

R-squared Value: 0.5390775849549849

We get a value of 0.53 which is not as ideal as we would want. This means there is at least some variability in the data that cannot be accounted for by the model. The value basically means about 54% of the model's prediction will be accurate to the actual Valence values.

In [230]:
prediction = lr.predict(x)
plt.scatter(y, prediction)
plt.plot(y, y, color="red")
plt.xlabel("Actual")
plt.ylabel("Predicted")
plt.title("Predicted versus Actual Valence")
plt.show()

It seems that there is not a close fit. The data points range throughout 0 to 100. So this plot does reflect the R-squared value we found earlier. We can see that there are some clustering of data points at certain points near the regression line. For example, we can see some clustering towards the 50% actual and 50% predicted.

Conclusion

Further Findings and Thoughts
¶

So unfortunately we are not able to completely conclude whether there are audio features or attributes that would clearly predict a song's valence. However, there was some interesting correlations found that could be researched into more. It was nice to see that Valence and Danceability complemented each other. Same with Valence and Energy. In hindsight, this makes sense at least to me when I listen to Pop music, I am trying to experience something positive. The predictive model we used was able to calculate a R-squared score of 0.53 which can explain some areas of Valence through some audio features.

Overall, the way someone views positivity of a song could very well be completely different to another person. It is important to remember that no song is universally positive for an individual. Additionally, songs can also change throughout its duration. For example, the Beats Per Minute can change or lyrics could convey a different message even if the song has a more upbeat instrumental. It is also critical to note that pop songs do not have to be positive. There are some great 'sadder' pop songs that can still put people in a good mood or cheer them up in other special ways. In the end, the way someone experiences the Valence of a song is subjective.

Hopefully this tutorial was interesting and fun to explore! It felt rewarding to code and explore my findings while wrapping up my time in CMSC320. I also enjoyed the EDA portion. It allowed me visualize stats that would not have made much sense to me unless I saw a nice graphic for it. I found a lot of insightful information especially to Spotify's music library as a whole. Maybe you were able to spot and find something captivating that I missed. If you want to explore the idea of predicting another audio feature, maybe try using the entire dataset or similar datasets with similar audio features available. You could even search for the top songs on spotify each year and see if Valence vary from different time periods. The next time you listen to a Pop song, don't forget to pay attention to the different audio features to see how uplifting the song is!
